   <titles>
      <title>Two Linear Equations in <math>
            <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
         </math> with Non-Parallel Normal Vectors</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we consider the simultaneous solutions of two linear equations with two unknowns</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
						\begin{array}{rcrcl}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_1$}{\color{red} x} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_2$}{\color{red} y} &amp; = &amp; {\color{blue} c} \\
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_1$}{\color{red} x} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_2$}{\color{red} y} &amp; = &amp; {\color{blue} d} \\
						\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>If the coefficient vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_1 = (a_1,a_2)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_2 = (b_1,b_2)</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel, we find ourselves in the situation sketched below.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/TwoEqnsR2NonParallel.gif" height="285" width="455">
                        <image.mapping>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="264,126,292,93,294,50,275,44,238,104,251,114">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The normal vector formed from the coefficients of the first equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly"
                                 coords="202,214,186,166,171,152,154,174,159,188,174,186,191,222,202,218">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The normal vector formed from the coefficients of the second equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="374,220,378,206,323,169,314,180,368,218">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>In <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                       </math> a hyperplane is just a line. This is the line of solutions of the first equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="302,153,242,114,106,14,98,29,284,157">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>In <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                       </math> a hyperplane is just a line. This is the line of solutions of the first equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="323,164,426,109,414,96,312,149,323,168">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>In <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                       </math> a hyperplane is just a line. This is the line of solutions of the second equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="300,181,146,262,138,250,200,220,288,168,299,176">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>In <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                       </math> a hyperplane is just a line. This is the line of solutions of the second equation.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="308,169,5">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Two nonparallel lines in the plane <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                       </math>always have a unique point of intersection. This is the one and only simultaneous solution of the two given equations.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                        </image.mapping>
                     </img>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The solution hyperplane of the first equation, with normal vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}_1</latex>
                        </math> is the line <math>
                           <latex>H_1</latex>
                        </math>, while</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>the solution hyperplane of the second the equation, with normal vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}_2</latex>
                        </math>, is the line <math>
                           <latex>H_2</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
            <para>
               <para.body>If the normal vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_2</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel, the lines <math>
                     <latex>H_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>H_2</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel either. So these lines intersect precisely in one point, denoted here <math>
                     <latex>(x_0,y_0)</latex>
                  </math>. This means that there is exactly one solution of the given system of linear equations, namely:</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>x = x_0</latex>
                  </math>   and   <math>
                     <latex>y = y_0</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Question</strong>   Amongst all the systems of two linear equations with two unknowns, "how often" do we encounter the situation that there is exactly one common solution?</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Answer</strong>   Exactly one solution occurs exactly when the solution lines of the individual equations are not parallel. Now, given two arbitrary lines in the plane, their 
				<subordinate>
                     <hot>chances</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>This statement has only intuitive value here. It can be made precise using a combination of the more advanced mathematical subjects of measure theory and geometric probability.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>
				of not being parallel are greater than their chances of being parallel. Therefore "most of the time" a system of two linear equations in two unknowns will have exactly one solution.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
